Consider a React class component `MyComponent`. If `shouldComponentUpdate` is implemented as shown below, when will `MyComponent` re-render?

```typescript
class MyComponent extends React.Component<{ id: number, name: string }, { count: number }> {
  shouldComponentUpdate(nextProps: { id: number, name: string }, nextState: { count: number }) {
    return nextProps.id !== this.props.id || nextState.count !== this.state.count;
  }

  render() {
    console.log('MyComponent Rendered');
    return <div>{this.props.name} - {this.props.id} - {this.state.count}</div>;
  }
}
```

A. When `id` prop changes or `count` state changes.
B. When `name` prop changes or `count` state changes.
C. Only when `id` prop changes.
D. When `id`, `name` props or `count` state changes.

A `PureComponent` receives `props.data = { value: 10 }`. In the next render, the parent component passes `props.data = { value: 10 }` again. Will the `PureComponent` re-render if `props.data` refers to a *new* object (even with the same content)?

```typescript
import React, { PureComponent } from 'react';

interface MyProps {
  data: { value: number };
}

class MyPureComponent extends PureComponent<MyProps> {
  render() {
    console.log('MyPureComponent Rendered');
    return <div>Value: {this.props.data.value}</div>;
  }
}

// Parent component example:
class Parent extends React.Component<{}, { obj: { value: number } }> {
  state = { obj: { value: 10 } };

  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        <button onClick={() => this.setState({ obj: { value: this.state.obj.value } })}>Update (new object reference)</button>
        <MyPureComponent data={this.state.obj} />
      </div>
    );
  }
}
```

A. No, because the `value` property is the same (10).
B. Yes, because `PureComponent` performs a deep comparison.
C. Yes, because `PureComponent` performs a shallow comparison, and the object reference has changed.
D. No, `PureComponent` would only re-render if the primitive `value` itself changed.

