```javascript
import React from 'react';

class DataFetcherComponent extends React.Component {
  constructor(props) {
    super(props);
    this.state = { data: null, loading: true };
  }

  // Problematic: This method is called before the component is mounted to the DOM.
  // If data fetching is performed here, it blocks the initial render.
  // In React's future concurrent mode, this method might also run multiple times 
  // or be interrupted, leading to inconsistent state or unexpected behavior.
  // Side effects like data fetching should ideally happen after mounting (in componentDidMount or useEffect).
  UNSAFE_componentWillMount() {
    console.log('UNSAFE_componentWillMount: Fetching data...');
    fetch('/api/some-data')
      .then(response => response.json())
      .then(data => this.setState({ data, loading: false }))
      .catch(error => {
        console.error('Fetch error:', error);
        this.setState({ loading: false });
      });
  }

  render() {
    if (this.state.loading) {
      return <div>Loading data...</div>;
    }
    if (!this.state.data) {
      return <div>No data found.</div>;
    }
    return <div>Data: {JSON.stringify(this.state.data)}</div>;
  }
}
```

**Why it's problematic:** Using `UNSAFE_componentWillMount` for data fetching is problematic because it runs *before* the component is actually mounted to the DOM. This means if the data fetch takes time, it will block the initial render of the component, leading to a blank screen or a perceived delay for the user. Furthermore, in future React concurrent rendering modes, this method could be invoked multiple times or asynchronously, making side effects like data fetching unpredictable and prone to race conditions. The recommended approach for data fetching in class components is `componentDidMount` (or `useEffect` in functional components) because it ensures the DOM is ready and the side effect runs only once after the component is fully mounted.

```javascript
import React from 'react';

// Using if statement
function NotificationIf({ hasNotifications, message }) {
  if (hasNotifications) {
    return <div style={{ color: 'blue' }}>{message}</div>;
  }
  return <div>No new notifications.</div>;
}

// Using ternary operator
function NotificationTernary({ hasNotifications, message }) {
  return (
    <div>
      {hasNotifications 
        ? <div style={{ color: 'green' }}>{message}</div> 
        : <div>No new notifications.</div>
      }
    </div>
  );
}

// Example Usage:
// <NotificationIf hasNotifications={true} message="You have 3 unread emails!" />
// <NotificationTernary hasNotifications={false} message="" />
```

The logical `&&` operator (`condition && expression`) is most appropriate and concise when you want to render an element *only if a condition is true*, and render *nothing* otherwise. It is particularly useful for small, inline conditions where there is no alternative UI to display when the condition is false.

**Scenario:** Displaying a loading spinner only when data is being fetched, or showing an 'unread messages' badge only when there are unread messages.

Example:
```javascript
function UserDashboard({ isLoading, unreadMessagesCount }) {
  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Dashboard</h2>
      {isLoading && <p>Loading data...</p>} {/* Only render loading message if isLoading is true */}
      {unreadMessagesCount > 0 && 
        <span>You have {unreadMessagesCount} unread messages!</span> /* Only render if count > 0 */
      }
      <p>Welcome back!</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```
In this scenario, if `isLoading` is false, or `unreadMessagesCount` is 0, we don't want to render any alternative UI; we just want those elements to disappear. Using `&&` is cleaner than `isLoading ? <p>Loading...</p> : null` or an `if` statement for each small, optional element.

```javascript
import React from 'react';

function UserProfile({ user, isLoading, error }) {
  // 1. Prioritize error state using an if statement for early exit
  if (error) {
    return <div style={{ color: 'red' }}>Error: {error.message}</div>;
  }

  // 2. Prioritize loading state using an if statement for early exit
  if (isLoading) {
    return <div>Loading user data...</div>;
  }

  // 3. Render user data if available, using ternary for concise display or && for optional parts
  // Using ternary for whether user exists, and && for optional email
  return (
    <div>
      {user ? (
        <>
          <h2>Name: {user.firstName} {user.lastName}</h2>
          {user.email && <p>Email: {user.email}</p>}
          {/* Example of optional profile image */}
          {user.profilePicUrl && <img src={user.profilePicUrl} alt="Profile" style={{width: '100px', height: '100px'}} />}
        </>
      ) : (
        <div>No user data available.</div> // Fallback if user is null/undefined after loading/error check
      )}
    </div>
  );
}

/* Example Usage:
<UserProfile user={null} isLoading={true} error={null} /> // Shows Loading
<UserProfile user={null} isLoading={false} error={{ message: 'User not found' }} /> // Shows Error
<UserProfile user={{ firstName: 'John', lastName: 'Doe', email: 'john@example.com' }} isLoading={false} error={null} /> // Shows User data
<UserProfile user={{ firstName: 'Jane', lastName: 'Smith' }} isLoading={false} error={null} /> // Shows User data without email
*/
```

