questions.answer:
Scenario: A component uses `useFetch` to post data, and its `options` object includes a `body` property that is an object. If this `options` object (or the `body` object within it) is created as a new literal on every render of the consuming component, the `useEffect` in `useFetch` will detect a new reference for `options` in its dependency array on every render. This will cause the `fetchData` function to run repeatedly, leading to an infinite loop of POST requests or excessive network activity.

Mitigation: The `options` object should be memoized using `useMemo`. For example:

```typescript
import React, { useMemo } from 'react';
// ... assume useFetch is imported

function MyPostComponent({ dataToPost }) {
  const memoizedOptions = useMemo(() => ({
    method: 'POST',
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
    body: JSON.stringify(dataToPost),
  }), [dataToPost]); // Re-create only if dataToPost changes

  const { data, loading, error } = useFetch('/api/submit', memoizedOptions);

  // ... rest of component
}
```

This ensures that `memoizedOptions` only changes when `dataToPost` changes, preventing unnecessary re-fetches.

