```
**Explanation:**
The `useNavigate` hook provides a function (`navigate`) that allows you to change the current URL programmatically. When called with a string, it will push a new entry onto the history stack. In this example, `navigate('settings')` is a relative path. If the current URL is `/dashboard`, it will navigate to `/dashboard/settings`. This is particularly useful for building flexible and maintainable nested navigation within your application.

```typescript
import React from 'react';
import { BrowserRouter, Routes, Route, Link, Outlet, useParams } from 'react-router-dom';

function UserList() {
  // In a real app, you'd fetch users here
  const users = [
    { id: '101', name: 'Alice' },
    { id: '102', name: 'Bob' },
    { id: '103', name: 'Charlie' }
  ];

  return (
    <div>
      <h2>User List</h2>
      <ul>
        {users.map(user => (
          <li key={user.id}>
            <Link to={user.id}>{user.name}</Link>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
      <Link to="123">Go to User 123 (Example Link)</Link>
      <hr/>
      {/* This is where the nested route content will be rendered */}
      <Outlet /> 
    </div>
  );
}

function UserDetails() {
  const { userId } = useParams();
  return (
    <div>
      <h3>Details for User ID: {userId}</h3>
      <p>This is where details for user {userId} would be displayed.</p>
    </div>
  );
}

function App() {
  return (
    <BrowserRouter>
      <h1>User Management App</h1>
      <Routes>
        <Route path="/" element={<h2>Welcome!</h2>} />
        <Route path="/users" element={<UserList />}> {/* Parent route */}
          {/* Nested route: matches /users/:userId */}
          <Route path=":userId" element={<UserDetails />} /> 
          {/* Optional: Default content for /users if no child route matches */}
          <Route index element={<h4>Select a user to view details.</h4>} />
        </Route>
        <Route path="*" element={<h2>404 - Page Not Found</h2>} />
      </Routes>
    </BrowserRouter>
  );
}

export default App;
```

**Explanation:**
- `BrowserRouter` sets up the history API for routing.
- The first `Route` is for the home page.
- The `'/users'` `Route` renders `UserList`. Critically, it has a child `Route` with `path=":userId"`.
- `UserList` component contains an `<Outlet />`. When the URL matches `/users/101`, `UserList` renders, and then `UserDetails` (for `userId=101`) is rendered *inside* the `UserList` component at the position of the `<Outlet />`.
- The `Link to={user.id}` within `UserList` uses a relative path, seamlessly navigating to `/users/101`, `/users/102`, etc., making the nesting intuitive. The example link `to="123"` demonstrates navigating to a hardcoded user ID.

